    &lt;strong&gt;High carrying capacity&lt;/strong&gt; allows for prolonged growth, with population peaks near or above 50. This can intensify transmission and TB mortality as more individuals are present to sustain spread.

    The carrying capacity directly limits total population size, but indirectly influences infection dynamics, as larger populations lead to more contacts and potentially higher disease burden.

    Mortality patterns shift with population density. At higher densities, both natural and TB-induced mortality tend to rise due to more crowding and interaction.

    &lt;strong&gt;Please note&lt;/strong&gt; that neither the parameters or initial population settings were changed which can cause an initial peak or fall in numbers.
